com.github.lecogiteur.csvbang.annotation
Annotation Type CsvFile

@Target(value=TYPE)
@Retention(value=RUNTIME)
@Inherited
@Documented
public @interface CsvFile

Defines options about writing, reading and file

Version:
0.1.0
Author:
Tony EMMA

blocksize

public abstract int blocksize
Size of buffer in number of record. Negative value means no buffer. By default -1

Returns:
the size in number of record
Since:
0.1.0
Default:
-1

asynchronousWriter

public abstract boolean asynchronousWriter
True if you want to write file asynchronously. By default false.

You can define the number of thread dedicate to write file in FactoryCsvWriter. By default the number of thread is the number of processor divide by 3. If you create several files in the same time, the thread will be share for each files.

Returns:
True if you want to write asynchronously
Since:
0.1.0
Default:
false

fileName

public abstract String fileName

You can define a static file name.

It is not required. You could define dynamically the filename in Factory.

It is possible to mix configuration. For example you can define dynamically the directory with the factory and a static file name with this annotation.

If a file name is defined by factory, it overrides the static file name created by the annotation

By default the static file name is "out-%n.csv".

You can define a pattern for the static file:

  • %n : the number file
  • %d : date format
Example: myCsvFile-%n.csv

Returns:
the file name
Since:
0.1.0
See Also:
FactoryCsvWriter, of CsvFile annotation
Default:
"out-%n.csv"

datePattern

public abstract String datePattern
Pattern of date to use for file name when you add "%d" in the file name. This pattern is based on SimpleDateFormat pattern. By Default, it's "yyyyMMdd".

Returns:
the pattern of date
Since:
0.1.0
Default:
"yyyyMMdd"

append

public abstract boolean append

True if you want to append csv data to a file (if it exist). If the file doesn't exist, it create a new file.

False, if you already want to create a new file. By default, it's false.

Returns:
True if you want to append csv data to a file.
Since:
0.0.1
Default:
false

maxRecordByFile

public abstract int maxRecordByFile

Max records by file. If the max number of record is negative, no max number of record is defined. By default -1.

There is no warranty that all full files in pool have the maximum records defined. But we sure that no file exceed the maximum of records.

Returns:
the maximum of records in a file.
Since:
0.1.0
Default:
-1

maxFileSize

public abstract int maxFileSize

The max size of file. By default -1.

If the max size is negative, no max size is defined. The size is defined in byte.

There is no warranty that all full files in pool have the maximum size defined. But we sure that no file exceed the maximum size.

Returns:
the number of bytes about a CSV file
Since:
0.1.0
Default:
-1

maxFileNumber

public abstract int maxFileNumber

The max number of file in pool file.

CsvBang can manage a pool of file and can write or read simultaneous files.

By default -1.

If the max is negative, no max is defined.

Returns:
the maximum of file which can be written.
Since:
0.1.0
Default:
-1

fileByFile

public abstract boolean fileByFile

When you set a maximum of file in pool, the maximum of records in file or the maximum size of file, you can define if you process file by file or if you process files simultaneous.

This option is deactivated if the maximum of files in pool is lesser than 1. You must have at least two files in pool in order to use this option.

By default, the value is true

Returns:
True if you want to process file by file
Since:
0.1.0
See Also:
maxFileNumber(), maxFileSize(), maxRecordByFile()
Default:
true
